{
  "answer": "**Charles Dunoyer's *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL II*, Chapter 16 (\"VI. De la liberté de l'industrie manufacturière\").**[^1]\n\nThis chapter contrasts French luxury-focused manufactures with English mass production by highlighting England's superior output despite a smaller population: \"England, with a population that is not half that of France, annually fabricates twice as many woolens, three times more *cottons*, six times more iron or cast iron.\"[^1] It specifically notes the Perkins comparison: \"A London brewer, M. Perkins, alone sells for nearly as much in beer as the three hundred and seventy-six butchers of Paris annually buy in meat at the markets of Sceaux and Poissy: while our butchers, according to the official statistics I have already cited, buy only 45 million worth of meat, the brewer of whom I speak sells 40 million worth of beer.\"[^1]\n\n[^1]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL II*, [paragraph](/works/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-ii-d6ae03/16-vi-de-la-liberte-de-lindustrie-manufacturiere/translation/#p-78e243).",
